{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4ddfe9a6-daeb-4298-adbd-c2181dfe4a01","content":"\n\nUse **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all your installed workloads to match the current SDK band. This is what you need after an SDK update, since the workload versions must align with the new SDK.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — only **reinstalls** workloads at their current versions to fix corrupted installations. It won't bump them to match your updated SDK.\n\nAfter updating, you can verify with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload list\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after the update, also try `dotnet workload restore` from your solution directory — it ensures all workloads referenced by your project are installed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6492f338-4093-4d49-a7d9-0b8f8d6ecbc9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after an SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a knowledge question, not a code task. I can answer directly.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions for the current SDK band. This is what you want after an SDK update, because the workload versions need to match the new SDK.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted installations. It doesn't change versions, it just re-downloads and reinstalls the current versions.\n\nSince the issue is that the SDK was updated and workloads are now out of date (version mismatch), `dotnet workload update` is the correct choice.","outputTokens":369},"id":"f12bbc95-1416-4981-80ba-020837e35274","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:47:09.814Z","parentId":"9784e8e4-a2cf-4654-b36c-b374cf099ca1"}
